\par \pard\plain \qc\sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 {\b On-line help is only available for the map screen
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 1.\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li360\sa120\nowidctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}You are in command of a force of 112 aircraft arranged into seven squadrons.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 2.\tab}In pursuit of your campaign objectives, you will design missions using this map screen.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 3.\tab}The day is organized into three sessions: Morning, Midday and Afternoon. Missions should be arranged for each session. Up to 96 aircraft can be used in each session.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 4.\tab}Some sessions will be lost due to bad weather. 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 5.\tab}The full range of Mission Types can be {\uldb designed}{\v HIDD_MISSIONGENERATION}. You can either design a mission from scratch personally or just set the overall parameters and let your staff complete the {
\uldb details}{\v HIDD_COMIT_E}.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs22\lang1033 6.\tab}You are cleared to fly missions in the following {\uldb aircraft:}{\v HIDD_RESOURCES} F86 Sabre, F80C Shooting Star, F84E Thunder Jet and the F51 Mustang.
\par \pard \sa120\nowidctlpar \page {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k} Main Supply Route; Close Air Support}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 $} {\b\fs32 Battle Scenario
}}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 #} HIDD_BATTLESCENARIO}}{\b\fs32 Battle Scenario
\par }Yo
u are supporting a ground battle that is being fought on the Korean peninsula. As the peninsula runs north-south you will find that the front line generally lies east-west. Although your specific objectives will vary from campaign to campaign, the overall
 objective is to support the UN ground forces in their effort to move the front line up to the Chinese border.
\par It is possible to support the ground forces by flying Close Air Support missions. This may be necessary when UN Forces are in danger of being over
-run. However this is not necessarily the best use of your resources. The Communist ground threat depends on getting supplies to the front line. Successful Interdiction missions can therefore delay a Communist advance and even force a retreat.
\par For the sake of convenience, three Main Supply Routes (MSR) have been identified. There is one on the West Coast, one in the Central Region and one on the East. Each Communist asset has been allocated to a route so that during briefings you will be able t
o determine its sphere of influence. Often the sphere of influence is obvious; sometimes though, because of the mountainous landscape, the connection is not immediately apparent. 
\par It should be noted that the Supply Routes do not operate independently. There are many cross-links that the Communists use to bypass destroyed bridges etc.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar \b\f5\fs36 \page {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k} Resources;Bombers;Fighters}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 $} {\b\fs28 
Resources}}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 #} HIDD_RESOURCES}}Resources
\par \pard\plain \sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 Your have five fighter squadrons and two bomber squadrons under your command. 
\par The fighter squadrons which are based in Korea, consist of:
\par \pard\plain \s49\li720\sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 Two squadrons of F86 Sabre Jet aircraft. These are the best air combat aircraft at your disposal. Sabres are only armed for air to air duties.
\par \pard\plain \li720\sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 One squadron of F84E jets and one squadron of F80C jets. These aircraft are best suited to ground strike duties. The MiG15 in combat outclasses them.
\par One squadron of F51 prop aircraft. These aircraft are no match for the MiG15 in combat. However they are useful for Close Air Support and Interdiction Missions close to the front.
\par \pard \sa120\nowidctlpar The bomber squadr
ons are based in Japan. On any particular day you will have either a squadron of B29 heavy bombers or B26 medium bomber aircraft available. B29s are preferable because they deliver a bigger punch. However if the attrition rate becomes too high they will b
e withheld.
\par Each squadron of pilots is organized into six flights of four. However, the maximum number of aircraft that can be launched at any session is sixteen and therefore only four flights can fly. This gives you the option of resting pilots. 
\par Aircraft
 are allocated in units of four, i.e. in flights. So, for instance, if you have designed four Strike Missions it would be possible to allocate two flights of Sabres to each mission. Alternatively you could allocate one flight to each mission and the remai
ning four Sabre flights could be allocated together to form a MiGCAP over MiG Alley. 
\par A flight consists of two elements of two aircraft. The leader/wingman element is the smallest fighting unit in MiG Alley. Although aircraft are allocated to missions in flights, it is possible to allocate duties to individual elements.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar \b\f5\fs36 \page {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 $} Missions_Generation}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 #}
 HIDD_MISSIONGENERATION}}Missions Generation
\par \pard\plain \sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 Missions can be generated in a number of ways:
\par \pard \li720\sa120\nowidctlpar By initiating Directives, the Mission Folder will be filled automatically.
\par Clicking on authorize on either the Target Dialogue or Dossier will produce the framework for a mission.
\par \pard\plain \s49\li720\sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 On the Mission Results Dialogue click on {\uldb redo}{\v HIDD_RESULTS} to carry the highlighted mission over to the next day.
\par \pard \s49\sa120\nowidctlpar If a mission is marked for {\i Redo, }then the aircraft required are automatically removed from the available set before the Directives automatically build the next session\rquote s missions.
\par No matter what method is used for mission generation, the mission can be fine-tuned to an extraordinary level of detail. Use the:
\par \pard\plain \s16\fi720\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\fs22\uldb {\*\bkmkstart debrief}{\*\bkmkstart mission}{\*\bkmkend debrief}{\*\bkmkend mission}Mission Profile Dialogue}{\v\fs22 HIDD_PROFILE}{\fs22  to insert and delete Waves}.
\par \pard \s16\li720\nowidctlpar {\fs22\uldb Task Dialogue}{\v\fs22 HIDD_TASKTABS}{\fs22  to change the aircraft types, numbers, duties and payloads.
\par }\pard\plain \s49\li720\sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 {\uldb Route Dialogue}{\v HIDD_WAVETABS} to make changes to the route for the mission.
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\nowidctlpar \b\f5\fs36 \page {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 k} Waves;Missions;Groups}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 $}
 Mission_Structure}#{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\nowidctlpar \f5\fs20 {\cs15\f0\fs16\up6 #} HIDD_MISSIONSTRUCTURE}}Mission Structure
\par \pard\plain \sa120\nowidctlpar \f5\fs22 Up to 10 completely independent missions can be set up for any particular session. 
\par Each mission can consist of up to six Waves. A Wave is made up of the Strike or Main Duty Group that can be supported by an Air Cover Group and an AAA Group. Each Wave can have its own ToT (Time over Target).
\par This system gives the flexibility to design either many small missions or fewer complex missions. 
\par Templates or {\uldb profiles}{\v HIDD_LOADPROFILE} can be produced so that you can easily regenerate missions.
\par The Mission Structure has been designed to allow you to generate missions that were typical during the conflict. For instance, due to limited fuel capacity, Combat Air Patrol aircraft could only stay on station for about twenty minutes. MiG pilots soon re
alized this and so they waited until the Sabres started to leave before mounting an attack. In this situation the Sabres were vulnerable because they did not have the fuel to stay and fight and also
 get home. To combat this tactic Sabres were organized into Waves so that as one Wave was ready to leave another was arriving.
